hit the US, but an A9/10 may have been able to do the job, especially<br>
if launched from Greenland.  There were plans to use a modified V2 <br>
(wings and a pressurized cockpit) to form the upper stage of a sub-orbital<br>
rocket capable of strikes against the US eastern coast.  The navigation<br>
system was a Luftwaffe pilot.  The plan was to use the wings to<br>
skip along the upper atmosphere to increase range.  The pilot/astronaut<br>
would drop a bomb after re-entry over the atlantic near the east coast<br>
of the US.  Then turn back out to sea, bail out and picked up by<br>
a waiting U-Boat.  This may have been possible by around 1950 had things<br>
gone badly for the Allies and very well for the Axis.<br>
<br>
As far as invading the US, I doubt it would ever happen, but the US<br>
coastal defenses were very poor.  Early on U-Boat commanders<br>
were able to enter New York City's water's and the German's commented<br>
on the ignorance of the US not to observe a blackout of it's major<br>
cities... New York glowed like a christmas tree at night... a perfect<br>
target had they so choosed.<br>
<br>
