<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>No, they were not.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ufx.org/images/a9_10.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A9/10 drawing dated June 10, 1941. Hypersonic A9 stage highlighted</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The intercontinental A9 was equipped with radically modified, highly-swept wings for a transatlantic glide beginning at hypersonic (greater than Mach 5) speeds and was nested in the nose of the A10. The A10 itself was about 65 feet long and was equipped with a 375,000 lb thrust rocket engine burning Diesel-grade oil and nitric acid. During its 50 second burn, it could accelerate the A9 to a speed of about 2,700 mph and an altitude of about 15 miles. With the A9 installed, the composite rocket would have stood about 84 feet tall.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ufx.org/images/a4b.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A9 prototype (A4b), Peenemunde, January 1945</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ufx.org/images/a9.10traj.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Chart shows performance capabilities of four varieties of V-2</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Intercontinental Capability</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Early performance calculations (probably made around the middle of 1941) for a two-stage A9/10 <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>&quot;America Rocket&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> with a metric-ton high explosive warhead resulted in the trajectory shown below. The 375,000 lb thrust first stage engine would accelerate the rocket into a ballistic path. The second stage would separate at an altitude of about 80,000 feet and would fire its own engine, accelerating to about 6,600 mph and climbing to a peak altitude of about 175 km., which would be reached some 500 km downrange. From this point the winged upper stage would dive to a minimum altitude of some 75 km at a distance of about 1,200 km from the launch site.<br>
<br>
The missile would arc back up to a 100 km secondary peak, after which it would push over into a long, shallow, high-speed glide toward its target, which could be up to 4,000 km (2,485 miles) from the launch site. This was insufficient to reach targets in the US.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ufx.org/images/a9.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Trajectory of a two-stage long range rocket with wings. Range: 4000 km</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ufx.org/images/usattack.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
 <br>
The range problem led to studies of launch sites at the western extremities of the Continent. Von Braun's back-of-the-envelope calculations for this contingency are shown above.<br>
<br>
Launch Site 1 - Peninsular site west of Brest, France, 48.45N 5W - used to attack New York City<br>
<br>
Launch Site 2 - Cape Roca, near Lisbon, Portugal, the westernmost point of continental Europe, 38.75N 9.45W - used to attack Pittsburgh and Washington, DC<br>
<br>
(Brest is approximately 3300 statute miles from New York City. Cape Roca is approximately 3600 statute miles from Washington, DC and 3700 miles from Pittsburgh) <br>
<br>
Redesign of the engine of the A10 provided both improved thrust and reduced liftoff weight, and the final trajectory, shown below, gave an ultimate range of about 5,500 km (3,400 mi) -- sufficient to reach New York. Possibly the intention was to attack the other targets with reduced payloads.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ufx.org/images/a9traj.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theredcomin>theredcomin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/3/03 5:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the Germans had won WWII?</span><hr size=1> Hitler could only have won WWII if he had stopped after the fall of France in 1940. At that time he would have had every prospect of eventually achieving an “understanding” with Britain if Churchill (who only became prime minister at the very time Hitler unleashed his Blitzkrieg on France) had been left with, essentially, no enemy to fight. In due course, Churchill would probably have been replaced with a rather more malleable government under Halifax, who had always wanted to make a deal with Hitler.<br>
<br>
It’s worth noting two things here: Firstly, Hitler did not really want to conquer Britain. He considered the British Empire to be a natural ally for Germany and essential for the stability of the world, viewing the British as a fellow germanic race that had shown the way to rule what he (and lets face it, most British and American people at the time) considered inferior races, at minimal cost as in, for example, India and Africa. Secondly, he said often enough that he did not understand sea-power; he wanted a partnership with Britain that would give him a free hand in Europe and leave Britain with a free hand on the oceans.<br>
<br>
However, after his conquest of France, Hitler began to make mistakes. Not least was to continue the war against Britain, in the shape of the Battle of Britain. The truth is that Britain was always the side most likely to win this; for instance, although there was a shortage of trained fighter pilots, monthly British aircraft production was already in mid-1940 greater than Germany’s, and even if the air battle had been won by Germany, there is no way they could have launched a successful Operation Sealion (invasion of England) across the English Channel against the crushing might of the Royal Navy. <br>
<br>
Of course Hitler’s biggest single error was invading Russia, but not far behind in the stupidity stakes was declaring war on the United States in the wake of Pearl Harbor. It’s almost certain that the US would have found itself at war with the Grossdeutsches Reich pretty soon after that event anyway (just consider the way America was being drawn into the u-boat war in the North Atlantic, for example) but it showed his vast ignorance of the size and power of the American military-industrial complex to call that down upon himself voluntarily. <br>
<br>
As for invading Russia, well! British Field Marshal Montgomery once said, after the war, that there are only three essential rules in European warfare, “One: Don’t invade Russia. Two: Don’t Invade Russia! Three: DON’T INVADE RUSSIA!!” Even without Anglo-American help to the Soviets, it’s clear that Hitler would eventually have got, at the very best, bogged down in the unimaginable expanse of Siberia. But almost certainly the Soviets would eventually have won. It might have taken a few years more than it did for them to get to Berlin, but the prospect of the Red Army on the English Channel by about 1950 is what that alternative future would have looked like.<br>
<br>
And if… no, when America had eventually woken up to the vast twin dangers of either a Nazi or a Communist hegemony across the Eurasian landmass, from the English Channel to the Bering Straits? A direct D-Day style invasion across the Atlantic would be beyond the resources of even the United States, but remember that the Manhattan Project was under way before Pearl Harbor. And remember that what drove the atomic scientists involved in it was the nightmare vision of a world where Hitler alone had the A-bomb. It’s reasonable to expect that the Bomb would be ready for use at or about the middle of 1945 as indeed it actually was, or very shortly afterwards, say 1946.<br>
<br>
Could it have been delivered on, say, Berlin? I think so. I think a B-29 flying from say Iceland (which was occupied by US troops before Pearl Harbor) could have made the round trip, which was similar in length to the round trip a B-29 flew to deliver one on Hiroshima. <br>
<br>
Could the Nazis have developed their own A-bomb? I don’t think they could, in the time and with the resources they had available which makes the subsequent arguments over the motives of their leading nuclear scientist (Werner Heisenberg, of Uncertainty Principle fame) kind of irrelevant. <br>
<br>
Could Wernher von Braun have developed the A9/10 two-stage rocket cum hypersonic glider to attack the United States? Yes, eventually, although the technical difficulties involved in making such a system work as specified should not be underestimated. But let’s be optimistic for him; with luck it might have been operational by about 1950, yet without a nuclear warhead it would have been pretty ineffectual—a pin prick, delivered at immense cost. <br>
<br>
It would also have been pretty inaccurate, if the performance of the V2s rained down on London were anything to go by. Laser guided precision bombing this was not. If New York was the target, you could have expected A9/A10s to land anywhere from Boston to southern Canada to Detroit to Virginia, with a goodly portion ending up in the Atlantic Ocean. During the testing stage of the A4 (the future V2) there was a serious problem with vehicles breaking up on re-entry, so von Braun decided to observe the problem for himself by going to the exact target point of the missile, which he reckoned would be about as safe a place to be as could be found. Of course he was right, and he could see the missile coming down a few miles away. What he saw led to the solution of the problem.<br>
<br>
In any case, the Germans had other ideas. The most practical, and most quickly implementable, was the sea launch of a V2 from the deck of a surfaced u-boat, about 100 miles or so off the coast of (say) New York. That might have been operational by about 1946, and would have been much cheaper and more accurate than A9/A10.<br>
<br>
But without an atomic bomb, neither of these delivery systems would have made any material difference to the final outcome. And in any case, the early atomic bombs were far too heavy to be lifted by either rocket system. The key to victory would not have been rocketry, but nuclear weapons.<br>
<br>
And so Hitler looses the war. <br>
<br>
After 1940, he just can’t win. Thank Heaven.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2193<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/4/03 8:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the Germans had won WWII?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The truth is that Britain was always the side most likely to win this; for instance, although there was a shortage of trained fighter pilots, monthly British aircraft production was already in mid-1940 greater than Germany’s...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
England's Fighter force was inferior to the German's during the Battle of Britain... the main reason that Britain was the victor was it's use of RADAR... they could launch intercept squadrons well in advance of the arriving bomber force and have an altitude advantage.  This allowed Britain to make the best use of a small air force combating a much larger German Luftwaffe.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but it showed his vast ignorance of the size and power of the American military-industrial complex to call that down upon himself voluntarily. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I fear that China is the next giant in so far as 'military-industrial complex' is concerned.  Their economy is growing rapidly and they have filled the area that the US used to occupy - manufacturing of goods.  The US is turning more and more to 'service oriented' economy... which is mostly worthless in a protracted conventional war.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Could it have been delivered on, say, Berlin? I think so. I think a B-29 flying from say Iceland (which was occupied by US troops before Pearl Harbor) could have made the round trip, which was similar in length to the round trip a B-29 flew to deliver one on Hiroshima.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It wouldn't be a question of range... more like could it penetrate a fortified Europe where Luftwaffe jets controlled the skies?  Perhaps the 'stealthier' B-49 would be a better choice?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.project1947.com/fig/yb-49.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Could the Nazis have developed their own A-bomb? I don’t think they could, in the time and with the resources they had available...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, they probably couldn't have in our real historical timeline... but in an alternative timeline where WWII lasts much longer, with a German controlled Europe... with the detonations of the US nukes on Japan as proof that it can be built, then perhaps the Germans may have yet developed the 'bomb' a few short years later... maybe by 1948...? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It would also have been pretty inaccurate, if the performance of the V2s rained down on London were anything to go by. Laser guided precision bombing this was not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You miss the main point of the A9/10 project... unlike the V2, it had one of the best guidance systems... a human pilot.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://meltingpot.fortunecity.com/seymour/32/sangerny.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Sänger Orbital Bomber, with bomb bay doors open, on its bomb run over New York City (Manhatten Island is visible just ahead of the Sänger's nose)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.luft46.com/misc/sang2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>1) Pressurized Cockpit     <br>
2) Oxidant Tanks     <br>
3) Fuel Tanks    <br>
4) High-Pressure Combustion Chamber of 100 Tons Thrust <br>
5) Auxiliary Rocket Chambers     <br>
6) Wedge-Shaped Wing     <br>
7) Retracted Undercarriage   <br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Free-Falling Bomb</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.luft46.com/misc/sang3.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The diagram on the right is part of Dr. Eugen Sänger's original proposal and shows the expected flight path that his &quot;Silverbird&quot; would travel on a bomb run to New York City. Please note the skipping, roller coaster-like path the Sänger would take before landing.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But without an atomic bomb, neither of these delivery systems would have made any material difference to the final outcome. And in any case, the early atomic bombs were far too heavy to be lifted by either rocket system. The key to victory would not have been rocketry, but nuclear weapons.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes early A-Bombs were heavy... but the Germans did posess a bomber that had the range and capacity to strike the eastern coast of the US and were working on more advanced bombers such as the Horten XVIII B 'Amerika Bomber'.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.luft46.com/mmart/horten2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>After 1940, he just can’t win. Thank Heaven.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As I have stated above, this is a hypothetical re-write of WWII, and as such I think it is safe to say that had the war gone differently for the Allies, and the Germans dominated Europe, unimpeded by Allied bombing of it's factories and research centers then the outcome is no longer certain.  A tiny little historical change such as the development of a large 4 engine bomber would have given the German Luftwaffe the ability to strike the Soviet Union's factories which they had relocated beyond the reach of German 2 engine bomber's.<br>
